**Code Explanation:**

The code begins by loading the TMD dataset and creating a binary indicator column is_dos_missing to flag the 16 missing dos_at_fermi values. Boolean columns (is_stable, theoretical, is_known_SC) are converted to integers to ensure compatibility with numerical operations. Categorical variables (phase, crystal_system, magnetic_ordering) are one-hot encoded using pandas. Next, all continuous features are identified by excluding identifiers, target variables, and the newly created encoded columns. These continuous features are standardized using RobustScaler to mitigate the influence of outliers. To perform KNN imputation (with k=5), a temporary dataframe is created containing the scaled continuous features, one-hot encoded columns, and boolean indicators. The KNNImputer fills all missing values in this temporary space. To verify the physical plausibility of the imputed dos_at_fermi values, the imputed continuous features are inverse-transformed back to their original scale (states/eV). The distribution of the 16 imputed values is then compared against the 186 known values using a density histogram with KDE, and summary statistics are printed to the console. Finally, only the dos_at_fermi column in the main scaled dataframe is updated with the imputed (scaled) values, preserving the NaNs in other columns like G_vrh for downstream tasks. The fully processed dataframe is saved to data/processed_tmd_data.csv.

